export const meta = {
  name: 'cross-model-challenge-autonomy-audit',
  description: 'Ladder the autonomy-grant pause-drift audit through Opus 4.8 then Fable 5 for adversarial cross-model challenge, each stage handing the next a compressed brief instead of raw source',
  phases: [
    { title: 'Opus 4.8 Challenge', detail: 'spot-check load-bearing claims against live repo state, write compressed brief' },
    { title: 'Fable 5 Verdict', detail: 'final judgment on Opus brief, not raw audit' },
  ],
}

const WS = '/Users/brien/Workspaces'

phase('Opus 4.8 Challenge')

const sonnetBrief = `You are auditing a root-cause diagnosis and a live fix written by a Sonnet 5 agent earlier today (2026-07-03) in Brien's Workspaces repo. Your job is NOT to re-derive the whole investigation. It is to adversarially spot-check the load-bearing claims below against the real repo state, then hand a compressed brief to a THIRD model for final judgment. Budget your reads: verify the claims listed, do not re-read the entire audit trail from scratch.

CONTEXT: Brien complained the AI keeps forgetting standing autonomy grants and pausing for unnecessary permission on work he already authorized. Sonnet ran a 15-agent research workflow, found the enforcement hook fabric is architecturally reactive-only (Claude Code hooks fire on discrete events, never mid-generation, so hedging can only be caught after it's written), found the lexical regex Stop-hook layer was frozen 5 weeks ago as unconvergeable, and found the one structural non-lexical detector (Layer 4.2) has been stuck warn-only for 35+ days.

CLAIM SET TO VERIFY (read the cited files directly, do not trust this summary):

1. Two prior calibration signals already exist and already surfaced the Layer 4.2 promote/retire decision to Brien as L2 (his call), twice, unanswered:
   - ${WS}/Core/frameworks/intent/.intent/signals/SIG-2026-06-12-layer42-calibration-review.md
   - ${WS}/Core/frameworks/intent/.intent/signals/SIG-2026-06-28-flight-model-30day-ratification-readiness.md
   Verify: do these files actually exist, and do they actually say what's claimed (decision_owner Brien L2, precision 0% on all fires, same stop-word/pronoun extraction bug)?

2. Sonnet found and fixed a real bug in the promotion recommendation itself: both prior signals' own false-positive tables lumped "team-configs" (a real compound noun) in with genuine stop-words like "each"/"that"/"all"/"with" without noticing it doesn't fit that class, so the originally-recommended one-line patch would not have suppressed that fire.

3. Sonnet patched the extractor in ${WS}/Core/frameworks/intent/hooks/autonomy-posture-check-layer-4.2.sh (look for "STOPWORD_TARGETS", added under a "§2.2b" comment block) with a closed-class grammatical exclusion (pronouns/quantifiers/prepositions/conjunctions), NOT another phrase list, and claims this is a principled fix rather than a repeat of the CHECK-1-through-7 whack-a-mole documented in ${WS}/Core/frameworks/intent/hooks/lexical-layer-freeze.yaml.

4. Sonnet claims verification against all 9 historical would_block=1 fires in ~/.claude/logs/autonomy-posture-layer42.jsonl shows 8/9 now correctly suppressed and "team-configs" honestly left as an open, unsuppressed candidate (not silently patched away). Re-derive this yourself: read the jsonl log, extract the 9 next_actions values from would_block=1 rows, and check them against the STOPWORD_TARGETS set in the live hook file.

5. Sonnet claims two git commits landed cleanly in ${WS}/Core/frameworks/intent (check with git -C "${WS}/Core/frameworks/intent" log --oneline -5) and one in ${WS}/Core/products/parallax, with the intent repo push blocked (behind ~24 commits, dirty tree from concurrent sessions) but the parallax repo pushed clean.

6. Sonnet's full report and proposed (unratified) DDR stub: ${WS}/Core/frameworks/intent/spec/2026-07-03-autonomy-grant-pause-drift-audit.md

YOUR JOB:
- Spot-check claims 1-5 directly against the files (do not just re-read the audit doc and trust its self-description; check the actual hook script, the actual jsonl log, the actual git log).
- Flag anything false, overstated, or incomplete, with file:line evidence.
- Flag anything Sonnet may have missed that a more careful model would catch (e.g. is the STOPWORD_TARGETS fix actually syntactically sound and does it actually run without breaking the hook's fail-open behavior? Is there a smarter fix for the "team-configs" residual that Sonnet dismissed too quickly as "separate, harder work"?).
- Do NOT re-litigate the platform-ceiling finding (reactive-only Stop hooks) unless you have a concrete reason to think it's wrong; that claim is well-established and re-deriving it burns tokens for no new signal.
- Produce a compressed handoff brief for a THIRD, more expensive model (Fable 5) who will render final judgment. That brief must NOT be a re-hash of everything above. It should contain only: (a) what survived your check as solid, in one tight paragraph, (b) what you found wrong or weak, with evidence, (c) the single sharpest open question left for Fable to adjudicate. Target under 400 words for the handoff brief specifically — Fable should not need to re-read the source files unless your brief flags something they must personally verify.`

const opusResult = await agent(sonnetBrief, {
  label: 'opus-challenge',
  phase: 'Opus 4.8 Challenge',
  model: 'opus',
  schema: {
    type: 'object',
    properties: {
      claims_verified: {
        type: 'array',
        items: {
          type: 'object',
          properties: {
            claim: { type: 'string' },
            verdict: { type: 'string', description: 'confirmed | overstated | false | partially-true' },
            evidence: { type: 'string' },
          },
          required: ['claim', 'verdict', 'evidence'],
        },
      },
      new_issues_found: { type: 'array', items: { type: 'string' } },
      overall_assessment: { type: 'string' },
      handoff_brief_for_fable: { type: 'string', description: 'under 400 words, compressed, for a model that has not seen the source files' },
    },
    required: ['claims_verified', 'new_issues_found', 'overall_assessment', 'handoff_brief_for_fable'],
  },
})

log(`Opus 4.8 challenge complete: ${opusResult ? opusResult.claims_verified.length : 0} claims checked`)

phase('Fable 5 Verdict')

const fablePrompt = `You are the final, highest-tier reviewer in a three-model ladder (Sonnet 5 wrote an audit and applied a fix; Opus 4.8 spot-checked it against the live repo). You are NOT being given the original audit or the raw source files as your primary input, by design, to keep this stage cheap and focused. You are being given Opus 4.8's compressed handoff brief below. Your job is to render final judgment: does this diagnosis-and-fix hold up, is anything still unresolved that matters, and would you sign off on it as-is.

OPUS 4.8's HANDOFF BRIEF:
${opusResult ? opusResult.handoff_brief_for_fable : '(Opus 4.8 stage failed or returned nothing — treat as unverified; state this explicitly in your verdict and lower your confidence accordingly.)'}

OPUS 4.8's FULL CLAIM-BY-CLAIM CHECK (for reference only, you should not need to re-derive any of this):
${opusResult ? JSON.stringify(opusResult.claims_verified, null, 2) : '(unavailable)'}

If, and only if, the brief above leaves a specific factual question genuinely unresolved that you cannot judge from the brief alone, you may use Read/Bash/Grep to check ONE specific file (the audit doc is at ${WS}/Core/frameworks/intent/spec/2026-07-03-autonomy-grant-pause-drift-audit.md, the fixed hook is at ${WS}/Core/frameworks/intent/hooks/autonomy-posture-check-layer-4.2.sh). Do not do a broad re-investigation. That would defeat the purpose of this ladder.

Render your verdict: does the diagnosis and fix hold up as production-worthy governance work, what (if anything) still needs Brien's attention beyond what's already flagged as his L2 call, and your confidence level.`

const fableResult = await agent(fablePrompt, {
  label: 'fable-verdict',
  phase: 'Fable 5 Verdict',
  model: 'fable',
  schema: {
    type: 'object',
    properties: {
      final_verdict: { type: 'string' },
      confidence: { type: 'string' },
      residual_concerns: { type: 'array', items: { type: 'string' } },
      sign_off: { type: 'boolean' },
      notes: { type: 'string' },
    },
    required: ['final_verdict', 'confidence', 'residual_concerns', 'sign_off', 'notes'],
  },
})

return { opus: opusResult, fable: fableResult }

